{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7914fedc-12a3-4807-bab6-6cc3e7c6b0c6","content":"Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file (or add to your existing one) like this:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `type: \"stdio\"` means Copilot communicates with your server via stdin/stdout.\n- `command`/`args` launch your server — adjust the project path if needed.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary, you can point `command` directly at the executable instead.\n\nOnce saved, VS Code will detect the server automatically. You can verify it's connected via the **MCP: List Servers** command in the Command Palette.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6d23b0ff-3e56-441c-abb7-dc688ebecc21","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to configure `mcp.json` to use their C# MCP server with GitHub Copilot in VS Code agent mode. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of VS Code MCP configuration.","outputTokens":277,"requestId":"C406:275D06:5201D4C:57E7AFA:69FBB47A"},"id":"712fc28e-c74d-4c17-a18f-d4f2526662a8","timestamp":"2026-05-06T21:37:05.587Z","parentId":"9b98cb2f-6352-4dcb-8ebc-672c882fe6f7"}
